Here's how each NIM model maps to its role across the stack:
Agent layer — inference core

llama-3.3-70b-instruct (FP8, TP=2, port 8000) is the primary reasoning engine inside LangGraph — handles SAR drafting, alert explanation, and multi-step AML investigation chains.
llama-3.1-8b-instruct (port 8002) acts as a fast auxiliary — quick classification, intent routing, and low-latency sub-tasks where the 70b would be overkill.
XGBoost via Triton FIL (port 8010) runs the fraud/AML risk scoring in structured-data mode — tabular features, deterministic inference, no LLM overhead.

Document layer

nemotron-ocr-v1 (port 8021) handles scanned KYC docs and bank statements coming through Apache Tika.
nemotron-parse (port 8022) does structured field extraction from parsed documents.
gliner-pii (port 8020) runs redaction before documents hit storage or the LLM context.

Graph + Vector layer

nv-embedqa-e5-v5 (port 8001) generates embeddings for Milvus — semantic search across transactions, entities, and case notes. Worth considering swapping to llama-nemotron-embed-1b-v2 for multilingual coverage (Bangla, Arabic, etc.) since you're in BD.
llama-nemotron-rerank-1b-v2 (port 8003) re-ranks retrieval results before they're injected into the 70b's context window.

Model selection rule of thumb: route to 8b for latency-sensitive paths (real-time tx scoring assist, UI autocomplete), route to 70b for quality-sensitive paths (SAR narrative, investigation summary, complex entity resolution).